 {"id":"bd-pou7j","title":"task(perf-foundation): define the comprehensive validation matrix and logging contract for performance work","description":"Background:
The current graph already includes several gauntlet and replay beads, but the validation obligations are still distributed across many tasks. That creates a planning risk: future implementation might satisfy local tests while missing the full matrix of unit, property, integration, E2E, soak, replay, and logging requirements that make performance work trustworthy.

Goal:
Define the canonical validation and logging matrix for the entire performance-control-plane program so every lane has explicit proof obligations and artifact expectations before implementation begins.","design":"Work packages:
- Map every performance lane and task class to the minimum required unit, property, integration, E2E, soak, replay, and shadow-comparison coverage.
- Reuse and align with existing observability/schema work so this matrix inherits stable IDs, event names, and failure-signature vocabulary rather than redefining them in parallel.
- Define the required logging schema for each layer, including stable IDs, reason codes, timing fields, mismatch categories, and replay pointers.
- Specify which tests are lane-local versus cross-lane, and which are gating versus informative.
- Require test scripts and gauntlets to emit human-readable summaries plus machine-readable artifact ledgers.
- Record failure-artifact standards so a broken optimization attempt is diagnosable without ad hoc debugging.
- Explicitly cover negative assertions and graceful-fallback cases so the matrix proves not only what should improve, but also what must not regress, what should remain stable, and what may intentionally degrade only within declared bounds.
- Require each lane to define minimum failure-forensics output, including how an operator distinguishes semantic regressions, observability gaps, benchmark overfitting, and expected challenge-fixture fallback behavior.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Future implementers can read this bead alone and know the minimum validation and logging obligations for any performance change.
